description:
File: lichen/subsys/lichen/schc/schc.c
Lines: 1495-1497

The function returns SCHC_ERR_TOO_SHORT when packet is NULL:

```c
if (packet == NULL) {
    return SCHC_ERR_TOO_SHORT;
}
```

SCHC_ERR_TOO_SHORT semantically means 'input data is too short to be valid'. A NULL pointer is not 'too short' - it's an invalid argument. This makes error handling harder for callers who want to distinguish between 'forgot to pass a packet' vs 'packet is truncated'.

Note: The base schc.c library has the same pattern, so this may be intentional consistency.

Fix: Return SCHC_ERR_INVALID_ARGUMENT for NULL pointers:
```c
if (packet == NULL) {
    return SCHC_ERR_INVALID_ARGUMENT;
}
```

Severity is very low - functional behavior is correct, only error semantics are affected.
